tool.name: UnzipFiles

param.name: ziplocation
param.dialogReference:
Click the browse icon to navigate to and select the directory folder containing the downloaded .zip files. For most Windows users, this will be the default Downloads folder.

  • Note that ALL files with a .zip extension in the ziplocation directory will be extracted. Make sure that you want all of the .zip files available in the ziplocation directory to be extracted to the same destination.

To set default values for this parameter, click on the Tool Help button at the bottom of the tool dialog box to display instructions (refer to Python Reference section).
param.pythonReference:
If you would like to set a default value for this parameter, you may edit the ASF_Tools.pyt script to add in your default download folder.

  1. Right-click on the ASF_Tools.pyt toolbox in ArcCatalog (or the Catalog window in ArcMap) and select Edit...

  2. Scroll down to ziplocation.value (line 43) and enter your download folder path between the single quotes (refer to comments in the script for an example)

  3. Save the script (select Save from the File menu in the script editor), then close the editor window

  4. Double-click the ASF_Tools.pyt toolbox in ArcCatalog (or the Catalog window in ArcMap) to expand the toolbox, and open the Unzip Files tool

  5. If you have double-clicked the toolbox and the change is not reflected in the tool dialog, close and re-open your ArcGIS application (ArcMap or ArcCatalog)

param.name: outlocation
param.dialogReference:
Click the browse icon to navigate to and select the destination directory for the extracted product folders.

  • Note that each .zip file has a folder inside to keep all of the files for that product together, so the resulting extractions will be a set of folders (one for each product) in the destination directory.

To set default values for this parameter, click on the Tool Help button at the bottom of the tool dialog box to display instructions (refer to Python Reference section).

tool.summary:
This tool unzips ASF products and saves the extracted folders in the desired destination folder. This is particularly useful if you are downloading multiple RTC files from Vertex and would like to extract them to a product folder.

  • All .zip files in the download folder will be extracted

  • Each product will have its own folder within the destination directory (when extracting ASF files, or other zip files that have a single root directory containing all the files within the zip archive)

  • The original .zip files in the download folder will each be deleted once file extraction is complete

-----

NOTE: If you have downloaded GRD or SLC products and will be using the SNAP Sentinel-1 Toolbox to process the products, do not unzip the product downloads using this tool. S1TBX is designed to work within the .zip folder structure, and this tool deletes the .zip files once they are extracted.
tool.usage:
Many ASF products are served as zip files, including Sentinel-1 RTC products generated using the On-Demand functionality in Vertex. Each product zip file contains another folder inside, so when the files are extracted, the individual component product files will still be contained within a uniquely-named product folder. Because the zip file and folder names are often long, standard Windows zip utilities may encounter errors if the full product pathway contains more characters than is allowed.

-----

This tool offers a quick and easy way to extract multiple zip files to the desired destination folder and delete the original zip files from the download folder. While designed to help manage ASF downloads, this tool can be used to extract any collection of zip files.

-----

If you have downloaded Sentinel-1 GRD or SLC files, and will be using the SNAP Sentinel-1 Toolbox to process the images, you will need to retain the .zip files. If you still want to use this tool to unzip the product files, make sure you've copied the original zip files to another folder first, because the .zip files will be deleted once extracted.

scriptExample.title: ASF_Tools.pyt UnzipFiles
scriptExample.para: This is the code for the UnzipFiles tool class within the ASF_Tools.pyt script.
scriptExample.code:
class UnzipFiles(object): def __init__(self):
"""Unzips ASF products downloaded from Vertex or HyP3.""" self.label = "Unzip Files" self.description = "This tool unzips ASF products downloaded from Vertex or HyP3 and saves the extracted " \ "folders to the desired destination folder. " self.canRunInBackground = True
def getParameterInfo(self): """Define parameter definitions"""
# First parameter: location of downloaded files ziplocation = arcpy.Parameter( name="ziplocation", displayName="Location of .zip files", datatype="DEWorkspace", parameterType="Required", direction="Input")
ziplocation.filter.list = ["File System"]
# If you would like to set the value to your default download folder, enter the path between the single # quotes below. Example: ziplocation.value = r'C:\Users\YourUserID\Downloads' ziplocation.value = r''
# Second parameter: destination folder for extracted products outlocation = arcpy.Parameter( name="outlocation", displayName="Destination folder for extracted products", datatype="DEWorkspace", parameterType="Required", direction="Input")
outlocation.filter.list = ["File System"]
# If you would like to set a default value for your destination folder, enter the path between the single # quotes below. Example: outlocation.value = r'F:\Projects\VertexData' outlocation.value = r''
params = [ziplocation, outlocation] return params
def isLicensed(self): """This tool does not require any special licenses or extensions.""" return True
def updateParameters(self, parameters): """Modify the values and properties of parameters before internal validation is performed. This method is called whenever a parameter has been changed.""" return
def updateMessages(self, parameters): """Modify the messages created by internal validation for each tool parameter. This method is called after internal validation.""" return
def execute(self, parameters, messages): """The source code of the tool."""
# Define parameters ziplocation = parameters[0].valueAsText outlocation = parameters[1].valueAsText
# Run the code to unzip the .zip products in the download folder to the desired destination os.chdir(ziplocation) for item in os.listdir(ziplocation): if item.endswith('.zip'): file_name = os.path.abspath(item) zip_ref = zipfile.ZipFile(file_name) arcpy.AddMessage("Extracting files from " + file_name + "...") zip_ref.extractall(outlocation) zip_ref.close() arcpy.AddMessage("Files extracted. Deleting zip folder " + file_name + " from original location...") os.remove(file_name) arcpy.AddMessage("Unzip complete for " + file_name)
arcpy.AddMessage("All extractions complete.")
return
